{"id":"d=origam-topic-3908//p=4d89bba2a7ea4983ae28ad12321d0f6d","tags":{"__document_id":["origam-topic-3908"],"__file_type":["text/plain"],"__file_id":["9be587ed35444d93af57501ed875c422"],"__file_part":["e791c1f2179640e69ba90eba91872c50"],"__part_n":["0"],"__sect_n":["0"],"source":["origam-community"],"topicId":["3908"],"categoryId":["61"],"url":["https://community.origam.com/t/how-to-run-ms-sql-database-server-in-docker/3908"],"title":["How to run MS SQL database server in Docker"],"imagesFound":["3"],"imagesDescribed":["3"],"imageUrl":["https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/b/b4d07452745ae3aef91c41fb98f2ccb502ff5012.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/3/365c50d26f04beb2fa3431a2d250c4c5e4c82ea0.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/d/dc4fd02e7e7600f078684fb449ce9365d1aee6d0.png"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":"# How to run MS SQL database server in Docker\n\nURL: https://community.origam.com/t/how-to-run-ms-sql-database-server-in-docker/3908\n\n@vikter (2025-01-16 09:25:13Z):\n   \nIn this article, we will show how to run a database server in Docker. A running database is necessary for any ORIGAM development. We will use both commercial MS SQL Server and open source PostgreSQL relational database system.\n \n In case you don\u2019t have Docker installed on your computer yet, please do it now. Here are general  instructions . \nIf you are completely new to Docker, you may find useful  this  and also  this  video. \n \n   MS SQL Server \n   Image download \n First, you need to download an image from which you can run your container. \n \n   If you have an M1 or newer Mac, check  this guide . \n \n In your command line (CMD or PowerShell in MS Windows or Terminal on MacOS), run the Docker pull command to download the image with the database server. You can use your own image, find any available in  DockerHub  or the following one: \n  docker pull mcr.microsoft.com/mssql/server:2022-latest\n  \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/b/b4d07452745ae3aef91c41fb98f2ccb502ff5012.png]\nDescription: The image depicts a Windows PowerShell interface with text displaying a command-line session. The visible UI text includes the following: \u0022Windows PowerShell,\u0022 \u0022Copyright (C) Microsoft Corporation. All rights reserved,\u0022 and instructions to install the latest PowerShell. The command executed is \u0022docker pull mcr.microsoft.com/mssql/server:2022-latest,\u0022 followed by progress messages indicating the image pulling process from \u0022mssql/server.\u0022 Specific identifiers include \u00223d29464607d8,\u0022 \u00223374dd749958,\u0022 and \u0022189521400cc7b,\u0022 all marked as \u0022Pull complete.\u0022 The status confirms the download of the newer image and provides a digest hash. The apparent purpose of the session is to retrieve a Docker image for Microsoft SQL Server 2022.\n\n\n  \n   Container creation \n Once the image is downloaded on your machine, you can create the container. Use your command line again, and this time run the following command. But before you do so, please replace the string  yourStrong(!)Password  with any password of your choice. \n  docker run -d -e \u0022ACCEPT_EULA=Y\u0022 -e \u0022MSSQL_SA_PASSWORD=yourStrong(!)Password\u0022 --name mssql2022 -p 1433:1433 mcr.microsoft.com/mssql/server:2022-latest\n  \n \n \nIMPORTANT INFORMATION ON DATA SECURITY ! \n It is important to know that all the data stored in the database running in the Docker container is stored only in that container, and if you lose that container (for example, if you accidentally delete the container), you will lose all your data as well. \n The solution is to use a Docker volume (save to an isolated Docker repository) or a bind mount (the database and data are saved to a local file on your machine). \n Example of using Docker volume: \n -v mssql_data:/var/opt/mssql \\ \n Using bind mount: \n -v C:\\sql-backups:/var/opt/mssql/backup (for MS Windows) \n-v $HOME/sql-data:/var/opt/mssql/backup (for MacOS) \n So if you want to keep your databases and data on your local disk and you are using MS Windows, create a container using this command: \n  docker run -d -e \u0022ACCEPT_EULA=Y\u0022 -e \u0022MSSQL_SA_PASSWORD=yourStrong(!)Password\u0022 --name mssql2022 -p 1433:1433 -v C:\\sql-backups:/var/opt/mssql/backup mcr.microsoft.com/mssql/server:2022-latest\n  \n The backup will then be in your local folder C:\\sql-backups. You can, of course, customize the name of the local folder in the script. \n Once you start the container with the mount, all changes in the database are immediately written to local files in your folder. \n Docker mount works in real time - you don\u2019t have to do anything manually. Every INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE is immediately reflected in those local files. \n So when you shut down the container and restart it, all the data will be there because it\u2019s physically stored on your machine in that folder. \n \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/3/365c50d26f04beb2fa3431a2d250c4c5e4c82ea0.png]\nDescription: The image displays a Windows PowerShell terminal session. ","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-05-01T23:36:15"},"vector":[-0.011809162,-0.011467375,-0.08732462,0.010592905,-0.03986469,-0.020963395,-0.015551135,-0.0026121517,0.023082545,-0.0008681562,0.0072656046,0.011003273,-0.036405798,0.023888525,0.00129418,-0.0063126837,-0.0068062474,0.029220704,0.012230422,0.022061622,0.0593449,-0.013584953,0.07430963,0.034432683,-0.011871602,-0.0073858565,0.025793307,-0.021795666,-0.018422032,-0.0132269105,-0.02535623,-0.023521204,-0.028378623,-0.013911103,0.01626996,-0.024343487,-0.009794054,0.014551624,-0.022755088,0.03026223,-0.019620856,-0.0384263,-0.002414581,-0.008052585,0.011571787,-0.028196739,0.01744502,-0.017231401,0.0343130